<leme no="559">   
<page no="a1r">
<section type="Title-page">
AN 
English Dictionary: 
EXPLAINING 
The difficult Terms that are used in 
Divinity, Husbandry, Physick, Phylosophy, 
Law, Navigation, Mathematicks, and other 
Arts and Sciences.
CONTAINING 
Many Thousands of Hard Words 
(and proper names of Places) more than are in 
any other English Dictionary or Expositor. 
TOGETHER WITH 
The Etymological Derivation of them from their 
proper Fountains, whether Hebrew, Greek, 
Latin, French, or any other Language. 
In a Method more comprehensive, than any that 
is extant.

By E. Coles, School-Master and Teacher of the Tongue
to Forreigners.

<lemeformat>
Ben. Johnson.

Much phrase that now is dead, shall be reviv'd;
And much shall dye, that now it nobly liv'd,
If Custom please; at whose disposing Will
The pow'r and Rule of Speaking resteth still.

Hor. <term lang="la">de Arte Poet.</term>
</lemeformat>

LONDON, Printed for Peter Parker, at the
Leg and Star over against the Royal
Exchange in Cornhill, 1677.
</section>
</page>

<page no="a1v">
</page>

<page no="a2r">
<section type="To the Reader">

<heading>
TO THE READER.
</heading>

THE several Climates of the World, have influenced the
Inhabitants with Natures very different from one ano&shy;
ther. And their several speeches bear some proportion 
of Analogy with their Natures. The Spanish and the Spaniard 
both are Grave, the Italian and th' Italians Amourous, the
Dutch as boisterous as the Germans, and the French as light 
as they themselves are. But the moderate Clime of England has 
indifferently temper'd us as to both: and what excess there is in 
either, must be attributed to the accession of something Foreign. 
Our changes are all professedly owing to the Conquests, especially 
of Sax and Normandy.

The first was far the greater, and by virtue of That the body of 
our Language is still Teutonick: But the Last is that which
more nearly concerneth us; because, though its first irruption
was not a violent Inundation, yet it forced us to such a
Communication with
France, that our Genius is wrought into some
resemblance of theirs: and
(to imitate them) we bring home fashions, terms and phrases from
every Nation and Language under
Heaven. Thus we should fill one
another with Confusion and Barbarity,
were it not for some such faithful Interpreter as is here
presented to the Prince of
Isles.

Not that I am ignorant of what's already done. I know the
whole Succession from Dr. Bulloker, to Dr.
Skinner, from the smallest volume to the largest
Folio. I know their difference and their Defects. Some are too
little, some are too big; some are too plain (stufft with
obscenity not to be named) and some so obscure, that (instead
of expounding others) they have need themselves of an
Expositor. The method of some is foolish, and supposes things
to be known before they are explained. For
</page>

<page no="a2v">
when the Terms of Art are reduced to their several Heads, you
must know (in general) what your word is, before you can possi&shy;
bly tell where to seek it; or else (as they say) you must look a 
needle in a bottle of Hay.

Suppose you want the meaning of Belperopis or Dulcarnon, 
they are not in the Common herd; where will you look them? 
In the Law-terms? they are not there. Sure then they are proper 
Names; But they are not there neither. What's to be done? 
Why, look till you find and you will not lose your
labour.

Some that pretend to correction and exactness, transcribe out
of others (hand over head) their very faults and all.

Hear how severely Doctor Skinner taxes one of them, --- <term lang="la">Solens 
hallucinatur</term>: and again, --- <term lang="la">Ridicule ut solet omnia:</term> and in ano&shy;
ther place, --- <term lang="la">ubi notare est miserrimam Authoris igno&shy;
rantiam</term>, &amp;c.

But that Man had but a little work, and so was bound to have
done it well. It is excusable in a World of Words to say that 
<wordgroup1 type="t" object="Wrong Explanations">
<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Contemptible and Contemptuous, Ingenious and Ingenuous</form> <xpln lang="en">are 
all one:</xpln></wordentry>  <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">that <term lang="la">Decomposit</term></form> <xpln lang="en">signifies Compounded of two other 
words:</xpln></wordentry> <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Emberweek</form> <xpln lang="en">is the week next before Lent:</xpln></wordentry> <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Froise,</form> <xpln lang="en">a pancake 
or tansie: </xpln></wordentry> <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Gallon,</form> <xpln lang="en">a measure of two quarts: </xpln></wordentry> <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Gomer,</form> <xpln lang="en">nine gal&shy;
lons (instead of one.) </xpln></wordentry> <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en"><term lang="la">Limbus Patrum</term>,</form> <xpln lang="en">where the Saints reside 
till the Resurrection: </xpln></wordentry> <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Nazareth,</form> <xpln lang="en">the place where Christ was
born, </xpln></wordentry> <wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Redstert,</form> <xpln lang="en">a Robin Red-breast, &amp;c.</xpln></wordentry>
</wordgroup1>

And a thousand more such, which simple Children would be apt
to contradict, but Men of Judgement (for whom they were 
not writ) know where the mistake might lie. Yet sure 't 
would have made his worship smile, to have readd, how that 
Argus King of P. for his singular wisdom and circumspection,
was feigned by the Poets to have had no eyes.

<wordgroup1 type="t" object="Inkhorn Terms">
<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Custode admittendo,</form> <xpln lang="en">a writ for the removing of a
Guardian.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Ejaculation,</form> <xpln lang="en">a yelling.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Eviration,</form> <xpln lang="en">a yielding.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Fidicula,</form> <xpln lang="en">a falling vulture.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Ichidian,</form> <xpln lang="en">the Motto of the Princes Arms.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Iopaena,</form> <xpln lang="en">a song of rejoicing.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Lungis,</form> <xpln lang="en">a tall slim man that has no length to his height.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Mayweed,</form> <xpln lang="en">like Cammomile in smell, but of a stinking
<damage>savour, &amp;c.</damage></xpln></wordentry>
</wordgroup1>
</page>

<page no="a3r">
So many there are of this Nature and so gross, that (let the
reason be what it will) they are altogether intolerable.

In that which I have done, I do not warrant absolute perfection. 
The pains that are taken in it, will appear at first sight. The ad&shy;
dition that is made to the number of words in former Authors of 
this kind, is almost incredible (considering the bulk) being raised 
from seven in th' Expositor to almost thirty thousand here; which 
is some thousands more than are in Mr. Blunts Glossographia or
Mr. Philips World of Words. The order I observe is altogether Al&shy;
phabetical; for that best answers the design of Informing others. 
If any would have the proper Names, Terms of Law, Navigati&shy;
on (or any other Art) by themselves, they may go through the 
whole and (with delight and profit) reduce them all to their par&shy;
ticular Heads.

I am no friend to vain and tedious repetitions. Therefore you
will often meet with words explain'd in their dependance and re&shy;
lation to one another, and the sence compleated by taking them
together: as for example,

<wordgroup1 type="a">
<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Lupa,</form> <xpln lang="en">a She-wolf that nourished Romulus in the</xpln></wordentry>
<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Lupercal,</form> <xpln lang="en">a place near Rome, where were celebrated the</xpln></wordentry>
<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Lupercalia,</form> <xpln lang="en">Feasts in honour of Pan, performed by the</xpln></wordentry>
<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Luperci,</form> <xpln lang="en">Priests of Pan---.</xpln></wordentry>
</wordgroup1>

Poetical expressions may be allowed to Poetical Relations and
Fictions; yet here and there I give a hint, to let you know, that 
I take them not for real verities.

The history of the Bible I suppose to be so well known, as that 
I only give the plain English of the Hebrew, Chaldee, Syriack 
and Greek Names.

Here is a large addition of many words and phrases that be&shy;
long to our English Dialects in the several Counties, and where 
the particular Shire is not exprest, the distinction (according to 
the use) is more general into North and South-Country words.

Here are also added all the Market-Towns (and other conside&shy;
rable places) in England, with all the places of note in other
Countries, especially the Neighbour Nations. Where it is to 
be observed, that (as Dr. Heylin saies of Hungary) it were in&shy;
finite labour to expresse every little place which the seat of a war
</page>

<page no="a3v">
gives occasion for History to mention.

'Tis no disparagement to understand the Canting Terms. It 
may chance to save your throat from being cut, or (at least) your
Pocket from being pickt.

I have not only retain'd, but very much augmented the num&shy;
ber of Old Words. For though Mr. Blount (as he saies express&shy;
ly) shunn'd them, because they grew obsolete; yet doubtless 
their use is very great: not only for the unfolding those Authors 
that did use them, but also for giving a great deal of light to o&shy;
ther words that are still in use. Those that I call Old Words are 
generally such as occurr in Chaucer, Gower, Pierce Ploughman 
and Julian Barns.

And whosoever has a mind, instead of them (or other vulgar
terms) to use expressions that are more polite; he sees what words 
are markt for Latin, Greek or French, and may himself make
such Collections as will be far more advantageous, than if they
had been gathered to his hand.

Finally, that I might be the more comprehensive (for here is
very much in very little room) I have signified the derivation of 
the words from their several Originals, and the Names of the Coun&shy;
ties in which they are used, by one or two of their initial letters; 
the meaning of which is exprest in the following Table.
</section>

<page no="a4r">
<section type="Identically-sounded Word-pairs">

<heading>
To prevent a vacancy, I thought good here to prefix a Catalogue 
of the most usual words, whose sound is the same, but their 
sense and Orthography very different.
</heading>

<wordgroup1 type="a" object="A">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Heard,</form> <xpln lang="en">for heared.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Hard,</form> <xpln lang="en">as a stone.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Herd,</form> <xpln lang="en">of Swine.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en"><emend err="erd onists">Cerdonist</emend>,</form> 
<xpln lang="en">Hereticks holding two contrary principles (a good and bad
God) in all causes.
</xpln>
<lemenote>
Form unrecovered: the catchword is "Cer-", 
but "Cererd onists" or "Cerdonists" is not a word. Cole appears to mean 
the Catharists.
</lemenote>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Easter,</form> <xpln lang="en">the Christian-Passover,
in remembrance of Christs [Death and]
Resurrection. On this
depend all the other moveable feasts, and the most certain
Rule to find it (according to the Church of Englands
use) is this: Shrove-tuesday is
alway the first tuesday after
the first new moon that happens
after January (whether that be in February or
March) and the Sunday following is Quadragesima
(or the first Sunday in Lent) and the sixth Sunday after is
Easter-day.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Pope Gregory,</form> <xpln lang="en">the XII <class type="etymlang" lang="it">I.</class> who made the year to
consist of 365 dayes, 5 hours, 49
minutes and 12 seconds. And
that the Vernal Equinox (which was then March 11)
might be reduced to March, 21 (as it was at the time
of the first Nicene
Council) he Commanded the 4th. to be the 14th. of
October.</xpln></wordentry>

a Constable.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Head-land,</form> <xpln lang="en">a point of Land lying farther out
(at Sea) than the rest, also that which crosses the ends of
the plough'd Lands.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Head-lines,</form> <xpln lang="en">the ropes that fasten the sails to
the yards.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Head-sailes,</form> <xpln lang="en">those of the fore-mast and
Bolt-sprit, which make the ship fall off from the Wind, and
(in quarter-Winds) are
the chief drawing Sails.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Head-sea,</form> <xpln lang="en">that which after a storm [and
sometimes before] runs
contrary to the present wind, here long ships go easiest,
because they'l ride upon two waves at once.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Head-silver,</form> <xpln lang="en">as Common-fine.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Head-pence,</form> <xpln lang="en">about 40 pounds collected every 3d.
and 4th. year by the Sheriff in
Northumberland
without any account to the
King, and therefore put down
by Henry the sixth.</xpln></wordentry>

two.)</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Lincolns-Inne,</form> <xpln lang="en">(having the two next) and the
Middle Temple, (with the last.) The
Outer-Temple is converted to
Essex-house.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Serjeants-Innes,</form> <xpln lang="en">two
higher Houses for the Judges,
Barons of the Exchequer and Serjeants at Law. These altogether
(saith Sir Edward Coke) make the most famous
University (for profession of Law only, or of any one
humane Science) in the
world.</xpln></wordentry>

Christians ordained by Pope

the sixth, every fiftieth year, and by Sixtus the
fourth (as it now stands) every 25 year, beginning it first
Anno 1475.</xpln></wordentry>

causes at the Common-Law, that is, all Civil causes (personal
and real) between common persons.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Lord Justice of the Forest,</form> <xpln lang="en">Justice in eyre of
the Forest, one which hath Jurisdiction over all the Forest on
this side Trent, and another over all beyond.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of Assise,</form> <xpln lang="en">sent (by special
commission) into this or that (but not his own) County, to
take Assises for the Peoples ease.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of Oyer and Terminer,</form> <xpln lang="en">
deputed (upon special and extraordinary occasions) to hear and
determine some particular causes.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" >Justices errants or in Eyre,</form> <xpln lang="en">were sent with
Commissions into the Country to determine the Pleas of the
Crown; for the ease of the Subject, who must else have com'n
to the Courts at Westminster.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of Gaol-delivery,</form> <xpln lang="en">sent with Commission
to hear and determine all causes
belonging to any cast into
Gaol.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justice of the hundred,</form> <xpln lang="en">the Lord or Alderman of
the Hundred.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of Labourers,</form> <xpln lang="en">
appointed to redresse their
frowardness, who would
either not work or have unreasonable
wages.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of Nisi prius,</form> <xpln lang="en">are (now) the same with
Justices of Assises. Some make this difference, that the first
have jurisdiction in causes personal as well as real, and
these (in strict acception) deal only in Possessory
writs.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of Trail-baston,
(f.</form> <xpln lang="en">draw-staff,) Inquisitours
appointed by King
Edward the first, on occasion of great
disorders in the Realm,
during his absence in the Scotish and French wars.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of the Pavilion,</form> <xpln lang="en">
authorised by the Bishop of
Winchester (at a fair held near that City) by virtue
of a grant from King Edward the fourth.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justices of the Peace,</form> <xpln lang="en">
appointed (by the Kings
Commission) to attend the
peace of the County where they dwell.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justicements,</form> <xpln lang="en">all things
belonging to Justice.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Justicies,</form> <xpln lang="en">a writ for the
Sheriff to dispatch some
special cause above the ordinary reach of his
County-Court.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justiciable,</form> <xpln lang="en">subject to
authority or Law.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justicium, Lawsteed,</form> <xpln lang="en">
vacation, a stay or ceasing
from ministration of Justice.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justifical,</form> <xpln lang="en">executing or
doing Justice.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justification,</form> <xpln lang="en">a justifying, clearing,
maintaining, making good or
shewing a good reason for.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justificators,</form> <xpln lang="en">Compurgators,
which (by oath) justifie the
Innocency, report or oath of another.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justinians,</form> <xpln lang="en">Fryers and Nuns instituted 1412 in
St. Justines, an Abbey at
Padua.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justinianists, Civilians,</form> <xpln lang="en">
Students of the Civil Law,
reduced into the Code
and Pandects
by</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justinian, -nus,</form> <xpln lang="en">an
Emperour of
Rome.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Justinopolis, Cabo
d' Isiria,</form> <xpln lang="en">
a City of Istria, built by the Emperour
Justine.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights Baneret</form> <xpln lang="en">or Bann-, made in the

Standard and making it a
Banner, and who may display their arms in a Banner in the
Kings army. They that are created under the standard of the
King personally present take
place of Baronets.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" >Knights of the Garter or</form> <xpln lang="en">St. George,

Under the Soveraign of the

Star (or rather the Sun.)</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Gennets,</form> <xpln lang="en">the most ancient Order

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Hare,</form> <xpln lang="en">
fourteen Gentlemen knighted
by king Edward the third in France, at the
shouting of the French which he thought was the onset
of the Battel, but was only occasioned by the starting of a
Hare at the head of their army.</xpln></wordentry>

</page>

Crown'd King of France on Whit-sunday, this Order
(though modern) is most used
now in France.

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of Rhodes,</form> <xpln lang="en">

of the Holy Land, and holding

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Ship,</form> <xpln lang="en">by St. Lewis in

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Shire</form> <xpln lang="en">or

(upon the Kings writ) by the Freeholders
of every County, to consult in Parliament (on

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Seraphims,</form> <xpln lang="en">by Magnus

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Star,</form> <xpln lang="en">a French Order with this

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Swan,</form> <xpln lang="en">the Order of the house of

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Sword and Baudric,</form> <xpln lang="en">a

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en" >Knights of Livonia or Sword-bearers,</form> <xpln lang="en">by

<wordentry type="h" joinnext="1"><form lang="en">Knights of the Temple,</form> <xpln lang="en">
Templaries, or</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights Templars,</form> <xpln lang="en">instituted by Pope
Gelasius or (as some say) Baldwin the 2d.
about the year, 1119. Their Office and Vow was to defend the
Temple, Sepulchre, and
Christian Strangers, but growing
vicious (after two hundred
years) were supprest by Clement the V. and their
Lands bestowed on the Joannites, of whom the Lawyers
purchased the Inne founded by the said
Templars in
Fleet-street.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights Teutonick, Mariani.</form> <xpln lang="en"> a mixt Order of
Hospitallers and Templars, to whom the Emperour
Frederick the 2d. gave Prussia,
on condition to subdue the Infidels, which they did. Th'
Elector of Brandenburgh was (at last) sole Master
of their Order, for
</page>

<page no="82">
at first they had three.
</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights of the Thistle,</form> <xpln lang="en">a French Order (in the
house of Bourbon) constantly bearing this Motto,

&amp;c.) depending on the

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights-fee,</form> <xpln lang="en">Inheritance sufficient to maintain
a Knight, by some 800, by others
680 Acres, such as had 20 pound per annum (in fee or
for life) might have been (till 17 Car. 1.) compelled
to be made Knights.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knights-fee,</form> <xpln lang="en">is also the rent that a Knight
paies (for his fee) to the Lord of whom he holds.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Knight-service,</form> <xpln lang="en">a Tenure (abolished by 12
Car. 2.) obliging a
man to bear arms in defence of
his Country.</xpln></wordentry>

void ground (without the walls) called Portsoaken Ward.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Nona, Decima &amp; morta,</form> <xpln lang="en">the Latin names of

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Non-ability,</form> <xpln lang="en">an exception
against any person, why he
cannot commence a suit.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Nonacris,</form> <xpln lang="en">an Arcadian
mountain, at whose foot is
the River Styx.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Nonage,</form> <xpln lang="en">a mans being under fourteen years in
some cases (as marriage,) and one and twenty in others.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Non-claim,</form> <xpln lang="en">a mans not
claiming within the time
limited by Law, as within a year and a day, &amp;c.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Non compos mentis,</form> <xpln lang="en">not in his right wits,
viz. 1. An Ideot by nature. 2. By sickness or other
accident. 3. A Lunatick,
having lucid intervals. 4. which (by his own act)
deprives himself, as a
Drunkard, but this gives no
priviledge to him or his
Heirs.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Non-conformist,</form> <xpln lang="en">one that doth not conform [to
the Church of England.]</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non distringendo,</form> <xpln lang="en">a writ of
divers
particulars, according to divers cases.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non implacitando,</form> <xpln lang="en">&amp;c. a writ forbidding a
Bailiff to distrein a
Freeholder without the
Kings writ.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non est culpabilis,</form> <xpln lang="en">
the defendants general plea
to an Action of trespass, utterly denying the fact.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non est factum,</form> <xpln lang="en">an answer to a Declaration,
denying that to be his deed, upon which he is
impleaded.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non Merchandizando,</form> <xpln lang="en">for Justices of Assize, to
enquire whether victuals be sold in gross or by retail,
&amp;c.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">None of the day,</form> <xpln lang="en">the third quarter, from Noon
to half Sunsetting.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Nones of a Moneth,</form> <xpln lang="en">the ninth day before the
Ides; In March, May, July and October, the six dayes (and in
other moneths the four dayes) next after the Calends or
first-day.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non liquet,</form> <xpln lang="en">it is not clear, (like our
Ignoramus) referring
the matter to another trial.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non obstante, <class type="etymlang" lang="la">l.</class></form> <xpln lang="en">

notwithstanding.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non molestando,</form> <xpln lang="en">a writ for one molested
contrary to the Kings protection.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non omittas,</form> <xpln lang="en">commanding the Sheriff himself to
execute a Writ delivered to a
Bailiff, but neglected.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Non-pareil, f.</form> <xpln lang="en">peerless, without fellow; also

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">Non-plus, <class type="etymlang" lang="la">l.</class></form> <xpln lang="en">(no more) the end of his Latin,
[to put to] silence.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non ponendo in assisa,</form> <xpln lang="en">to free, men (by reason

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non principiate,</form> <xpln lang="en">

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="la">Non procedendo,</form> <xpln lang="en">

length
exceeds its breadth, the most proper are these, 1.
Sesquialtera, 2. Sesquitertia, 3. Sesquiquarta, 4. Diagonial
(increased to the length of the Diagonal of the single square)
5. Superbittens tertias,
6. Dupla, which is a double square.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="en">By Prorogation</form> <xpln lang="en">(in open Court) there is a
Session, and then such Bills as had not Royal assent, must
(the next assembly) begin again: But in Adjournment (or
Continuance) there is no Session, and therefore all things
continue in their former state. For every several Session of
Parliament is (in Law) a several
Parliament.</xpln></wordentry>
